entry.title: Convert FixedFlatMap to a regular flat_map in ToolbarController tests.
entry.content:
MakeFixedFlatSet is only for building compile time maps. As such, there

are restrictions on when it can be used: in particular, the set itself

must be constructed with a constant expression. Unfortunately,

ui::ElementIdentifier internally uses the address of a constexpr

variable. While the standard permits constant-evaluated contexts to use

the address of a constexpr variable, implementations are allowed to

treat the actual value of the address as 'unspecified'. This means that

the result of comparing the address of two constexpr variables is

unspecified, e.g.



inline constexpr const char kString1[] = "Hello";

inline constexpr const char kString2[] = "World";



// error: comparison between '&kString1[0]' and '&kString2[0]' has

// unspecified value

constexpr bool greater = kString1 > kString2;



Since fixed flat map needs to perform comparisons to build the map, it

is not possible to use ui::ElementIdentifier to initialize a constexpr

FixedFlatMap.



Rather than trying to rework ui::ElementIdentifier, just use a static

base::flat_map. This creates a static initializer, but in test-only

code, this is an acceptable tradeoff.

moved to helper methods, but due to moving it to helper methods this CL

is very large. The logic with VCN enabled is obviously new so I added a

test in CardViewControllerEGTest to confirm everything is showing as

intended. The VCN 'learn more' text is not aligned with the labels,

will align it in a small follow up CL.

entry.title: Protected Audience: improve performance of split signals fetch
entry.content:
The code to fetch trusted signals URLs is O(n^2) when kFledgeSplitTrustedSignalsFetchingURL is enabled. This stems from TrustedSignalsRequestManager::RequestsURLSizeIsTooBig which is called O(n) times and includes O(n) set insertions and builds a URL each time (also O(n)).



This change eliminates extraneous std::set operations that were used in the process of splitting trusted signals requests and organizes the code to more easily make future improvements such as:

- When checking if including a request in a trusted signals URL makes it too large, estimate the size of a URL in certain cases instead of building the URL each time

- Avoid rebuilding a URL if it was already built in the process of checking if the URL was too large.

entry.title: Prepare to convert SBThreatType to an enum class in ['/chrome/browser/ui/webui/interstitials', '/ios/components/security_interstitials']
entry.content:
It's somewhat difficult to log an SBThreatType as an UMA histogram since

we don't have a kMaxValue. We can't simply add a kMaxValue because

SBThreatType is an enum instead of enum class, and we'd be exposing a

constant safe_browsing::kMaxValue. This CL prepares to convert

SBThreatType to an enum class in ['/chrome/browser/ui/webui/interstitials', '/ios/components/security_interstitials'].



That requires two changes:



- SBThreatType is no longer implicitly convertible to int, so we will

need a few static casts



- SBThreatType values are now in the namespace

safe_browsing::SBThreatType instead of just safe_browsing. In some

places this is fixed by adding the new namespace, and in some places

with a "using enum" declaration. We can't just add a "using enum" for

all usages of SBThreatType because "using enum" would declare a

constant kMaxValue. So "using enum" is only used when many

SBThreatType constants are used, and in as narrow a scope as possible.



This CL was uploaded by git cl split.

entry.title: Plumb forced colors state to NativeTheme paint methods
entry.content:
This CL plumbs the forced colors state that exists as a web setting to

NativeThemeFluent's PaintScrollbarTrack() and PaintButton() methods.

Currently, these methods rely on the global NativeTheme web instance

forced colors state for handling specific painting operations. However,

this approach poses a challenge because the forced colors state within

Blink has evolved beyond the global NativeTheme web instance — it also

considers the page colors block list. Consequently, forced colors has

been implemented as a web setting within Blink(see CL:5324688).

Additionally, given that forced colors can be triggered directly in

Blink via the DevTools emulation feature, there is a need to make

these paint methods aware of this state.



To address this, we pass the forced colors state to these methods.



This change can be summarized into the following two tasks:

1.) Pass the forced colors web setting to WebThemeEngine::Paint methods

2.) Further propagation to NativeThemeFluent's PaintScrollbarTrack()

and PaintButton() methods

entry.title: [Extensions] Remove chrome.tabs.getSelected from most tests.
entry.content:
This CL replaces chrome.tabs.getSelected with chrome.tabs.query using

the following patterns:



1. If the window ID parameter is unused, call c.t.q with {active: true}.



2. If it is used, call c.t.q with {active: true, windowId: winId}.



3. Update the name of the parameter from 'tab' to 'tabs'.



In some tests, a convenience variable is defined to avoid changing too

many lines in the test:



const tab = tabs[0];



This CL explicitly leaves two tabs API tests unchanged to ensure

test coverage until support for MV2 is removed.
